# `.steno` format reference

The `.steno` file format defines stenography dictionaries as line-oriented entry blocks, directives, comments, and blank lines. Entries are parsed by [`crates/steno/src/parse/`](../crates/steno/src/parse/); the code plus [`stroke/`](../crates/steno/src/stroke/) and [`dict.steno`](../dict.steno) header are ground truth — this document is normative but subordinate to the implementation.

An **entry** is a fenced block: opening fence (four or more backticks followed by a non-empty stroke), template body lines, closing fence (backticks with nothing after trim). The stroke is split on `/` into sub-strokes, trimmed, empty segments dropped; e.g., `STKWR-PBGS/-FLT` yields `["STKWR-PBGS", "-FLT"]`. Sub-strokes are canonical Plover steno in fixed key order (left bank `# S T K P W H R`, middle `A O * E U`, right bank `F R P B L G T S D Z`). The hyphen separates right-bank keys only when no middle key is present; with a middle, no hyphen. Strokes are re-rendered canonical after count keys merge in.

A **directive** is a line starting with `@` (after trim); it attaches to the entry immediately above. Name runs to the first non-`[A-Za-z0-9_]`; the rest (trimmed) is the argument. `@count KEYS` fans the entry over a count bank; `@arity N` sets type-arg count; `@multiline`, `@type`, `@noarg`, `@fuse`, `@literal` are boolean flags. Count keys are LSB-first per bit position: `@count AOEU` → A=1, O=2, E=4, U=8, encoding counts 0..15. Keys must be middle (`A O * E U`) or right-bank (`F R P B L G T S D Z`). Counts merge into the entry's last sub-stroke and it re-renders canonical.

Template operators within block bodies: `%0`–`%9` are landing points, `%d` is count digit (0-based index inside repeats, total outside), `%t` is type slot, `%b` is body break, `%p` is destructuring pattern, `%[sep|body%]` repeats body per count, `%(EXPR)` is computed landing (linear in `d`, resolves at expansion). Raw `{` and `}` are structural braces. Backslash escapes: `\n` → newline, `\t` → tab, `\{ \} \% \| \\ \`` → literal; any other escape is an error. Unterminated `%[…%]` or `%(…)`, unknown `%x` operators, and trailing backslash are errors with source line and column.